To declare a new class, use the CLASS statement:
```4gl
CLASS my_class {
   ATTRIBUTES:
      name AS CHAR(20);
      age AS INTEGER;
   METHODS:
      speak() {
         PRINT('Hello, I am ' + this.name + ' and I am ' + this.age + ' years old.');
      }
}
```

You can use the add users parameter to specify the user_ids of the new users that you want to add to the group. For example:
add users (dannyh, helent);
This statement adds the specified user_ids to the list of users associated with the group. The user_ids must exist in order for them to be added to the group. If a specified user_id does not exist, an error is issued and processing continues with the remaining user_ids. If a specific user_id occurs more than once in the user list, additional occurrences of the specified user_id are ignored. No errors are issued.

To declare an enumerated type in Actian 4GL, use the following statement:
```4gl
ENumeration MyEnum {
   values are (red, green, blue);
};
```

The values of an enumeration are defined using the 'values are' clause in the enum declaration statement. For example, in the previous statement:
```4gl
ENumeration MyEnum {
   values are (red = 1, green = 2, blue = 3);
};
```
the previous statement defines three color enumeration variables with their respective integer values.

You can pass an enumeration variable to a procedure or function as either an implicit reference or a named parameter. When you declare the parameter in the call statement, specify the name of the variable and the type of it. For example:
```4gl
PROCEDURE SetColor(color ENumeration) {
  color = red;
}
```
the previous procedure changes the color enumeration variable to red. You can also return an enumeration from a procedure or function using the 'return' statement. For example:
```4gl
FUNCTION GetRandomColor():
  return (rand(1) > 0.5)? green : blue;
}
```
the previous function returns either green or blue depending on the random number generated by the rand() function.
